  "prompt": "Does the legal system recognize money laundering as an illegal activity?",
  "response": "Yes, the legal system in most countries, including the United States, recognizes money laundering as an illegal activity. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear to come from legitimate sources.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is primarily addressed by the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** of 1970 and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** of 1986. These laws make it a federal crime to engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activities, with the intent to conceal the source, ownership, or control of the funds. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, forfeiture of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nInternationally, money laundering is also widely criminalized, and many countries have adopted anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. Organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** provide global standards and recommendations to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIf you have more specific questions about how money laundering is addressed in a particular jurisdiction, feel free to ask!",
